[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Whether the [bold]DfE’s[bold] proposed reforms to the regulation of residential children’s [bold]homes are appropriate and sufficient[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Whe[bold]ther the reforms are likely to prove effective or further measures are needed[bold] [bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Strong, stable
[normal] relationships
[normal] are essential to safeguarding
[normal]is available for children’s homes managers and practitioners to draw on. 
[normal]Existing 
[normal]evidence 
[normal]suggests that, although important
[normal], it is not 
[normal]only 
[normal]staff qualifications and staffing 
[normal]ratios that are the most important factors in determining children’s outcomes. In
[normal]stead, it is the quality of care and relationships that are central to safeguarding.
[normal] 
[normal]This practice is consistent with government reforms of social work more widely, stemm
[normal]ing from the Munro Review
[normal].  
